The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 24, 2004 				 Puma puts its best foot forward
 RAJA GHOSHAL 				 	 Big strides																								New Delhi, May 23: German sports shoes and apparel major Puma, which is in its third year of operations in India, has carved out a plan to open 10 exclusive outlets across the country in about three years. E. N. Woodcock, general manager, Puma, Far East, told The Telegraph that, India is one of the fastest growing market for Puma, along with China. 																								He said the Indian operation of Puma has grown by 65 per cent in the first quarter of this year. We expect to grow by 100 per cent by the end of the year, he added. However, he did not give the sales turnover figure. The Puma market in China is also growing at a rate of 100 per cent. 																								Sources said Puma is planning a long-term strategy of opening about 50 outlets in India in the next 10 years. Essentially a lifestyle product, Puma shoes are priced between Rs 750 and Rs 4000 and apparels between Rs 400 and Rs 2000. 																								Planet Sports is the franchisee partner of Puma in India. Puma products are available in about 20 Planet Sports outlets and about 30 multi-brand outlets. 																								Puma, which distributes its products in more than 80 countries, uses outsourced production facilities in over 30 countries.																								Woodcock said the company has also launched its Italia range of products in the country. The company is the sponsor of the Italian soccer team for the Euro 2004 tournament that begins in Portugal in June. 																								Italia is a worldwide launch, comprising soccer shirts, T-shirts, soccer balls, mens apparels and sports kit bags. These products have been priced between Rs 1000 and Rs 2000, said Woodcock. 																								At present, the biggest market for Puma in the Southeast Asian region is Japan, said Woodcock. The other markets in the region where the company plans to expand include Korea, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore and the Philippines.
